Why doesn't the Fed do its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new board members of the US central bank Federal Reserve gives people in America – and the US Congress – the opportunity to think about the world's most important central bank and its future path.
The obvious question to be asked first is how it was possible for the Fed to so badly fail in its most important mandate - ensuring price stability.
That the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation suggests a fundamental failure.
Institutional soul-searching is undoubtedly in order now.
While monetary policy makes headlines, the Fed is now primarily significant as a financial regulator.
Another big question is therefore whether it will use its enormous power to drive climate or social policy forward.
The Fed could, for example, refuse loans to companies in the fossil fuel energy sector, it could require banks to only grant loans to companies with certified net-zero emission plans, or steer lending towards desired alternatives.
Furthermore, it could decide to explicitly take up its regulatory activity in the name of equality or ethnic justice by telling banks where and to whom to lend, who to hire, and who to fire, and so on.
However, before we turn to the question of which direction Fed regulation will or should move in, it is first necessary to clarify the Fed's serious failure.
In the year 2008, the US government made a far-reaching decision: financial institutions could still obtain the money for risky investments primarily through the sale of short-term, interest-rate-sensitive bonds, but hordes of new regulatory bodies would henceforth evaluate the riskiness of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory bodies would no longer overlook large problems like the subprime mortgages on bank balance sheets.
However, over the next ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the Fed's regulatory army never once asked itself what would actually happen in the event of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually occurred at the beginning of 2020, the Fed abandoned its "never again" promises from 2008 and intervened on an even greater scale.
In March, commercial banks proved unable to act as intermediaries in the market for normal US government bonds.
The Fed therefore supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. Corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms had been postponed for a long time.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed saved the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but it never happened.
The Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially providing a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes".
In 2008, the Fed and the US Treasury Department had resisted the idea of raising the market price of all mortgages as part of the financial sector rescue package - the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
However, in 2020, the "Powell put" - among other things - introduced an explicit floor for corporate bond prices.
The predictable response to this criticism will be: So what?
The lockdowns due to COVID-19 could have indeed triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks because the Fed and the US Treasury Department will simply put out every new fire with a new flood of money.
The problem lies, however, in the incentives that these strategies have created.
What's the point of bothering to save money or use balance sheet capacity to buy at falling prices, provide liquidity, or treat a "fire sale" as an "opportunity to buy"?
The Fed will simply outdo everyone else and pocket the profits.
Why would companies issue stocks when they can simply take a loan, knowing that the state will support their debts or bail them out, as was the case with airlines?
Why would investors hesitate when buying dubious papers, when their value is guaranteed in bad times by another "Whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed?
It's no wonder America is sinking in debt.
Everyone assumes that taxpayers will bear the losses when the next downturn comes.
Student loans, government pensions, and mortgages are piling up and waiting for Uncle Sam's rescue operation to come their turn.
But every new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will eventually refuse to put more money into rescue operations, and people will not be pleased with billions of newly printed money.
If the expected rescue packages fail to materialize, we will wake up to a firestorm – and the fire department will be burned down.
In 2008, at least regulatory authorities and lawmakers recognized the moral risk and worried that in good times investors would reap profits while in bad times taxpayers would bear the losses.
In 2020, people were only smug about the rescue operations.
The very Fed that failed to see the risks of subprime mortgages in 2008, just as it failed to see the pandemic of 2020 and now wants to conduct stress tests for "climate risks," will certainly overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy, or another disruptive event.
The regulators of the Fed do not even raise the question about these events.
And although word salads are produced about "networks," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles," they have failed to define the "systemic" risk, apart from it becoming a catchphrase that grants regulatory authorities all-encompassing power.
Regulatory authorities will never be able to foresee risks, accurately assess the value of financial institutions, or ensure that immense debts can always be repaid.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always stands ready to bail out debt mountains in bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
A better regulation can bridge partisan divides.
The Left is right when it says that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit most Americans very little.
However, it is based on the wrong cause.
A huge effort to comply with regulations is a major obstacle to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is futile.
Regulatory provisions are either smart or dumb, effective or ineffective, filled with unwanted consequences or well-designed.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and does not require regulatory authorities to have clairvoyant abilities.
The Fed has scandalously stopped companies in the Narrow Banking and payment services sectors that could contribute to meeting the financial needs of many people in America.
Before it devotes itself to saving the planet and making amends for injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how poorly it fulfills its basic task of protecting the financial system.
